{
  "answer": "Iqbal's *Khitāb ba Jawānān-e-Islām* (\"An Address to the Muslim Youth\") rebukes modern Muslim youth for their inertia, contrasting it with their ancestors' dynamic conquests and unyielding pride—even in poverty.[^1] The most demanding imperative is the implicit call to embody that ancestral spirit of relentless action over mere words: \"you are all talk, they were all action; you are static, they were ever-moving.\"[^2]\n\nManu, in Book 2 of the *Manusmṛti*, details the *brahmacārin* (celibate Vedic student), whose life centers on guru-service, alms-begging, sense-restraint, ritual purity, and total sexual continence.[^3] The most demanding stricture—underpinning the entire stage—is absolute celibacy: \"He should sleep alone everywhere and should never spill his seed; even unintentionally in dreams, he must ritually atone, lest he break his vow.\"[^4]\n\nNeither could realistically live up to the other's code. Iqbal's youth is summoned to worldly revivalism: \"World-seizers and world-rulers, world-guardians and world-adorners,\" scorning stasis for imperial, poverty-proud activism.[^5] This clashes with the *brahmacārin*'s inward, guru-bound asceticism, begging, and sensory mortification (e.g., \"Desire is never pacified by the enjoyment of desires, but grows ever stronger\"; \"if even one of all the senses gives way... his wisdom flows away\").[^6][^7] Conversely, Manu's youth vows lifelong studentship in Vedic isolation until marriage, incompatible with Iqbal's umma-spanning militancy. Shared threads like voluntary poverty exist, but the telos diverges: one builds civilizational glory through faith-driven motion; the other, ritual purity for otherworldly ascent.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/13-khitab-ba-jawanan-e-islam/translation/#p-0291d8).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/13-khitab-ba-jawanan-e-islam/translation/#p-365462).\n\n[^3]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 2 [chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/).\n\n[^4]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 2 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-51cabf).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/13-khitab-ba-jawanan-e-islam/translation/#p-365462).\n\n[^6]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 2 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-f445d2).\n\n[^7]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 2 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-2e26d1).",
